Terraform Interview Notes (IaC)
1️⃣ What is Infrastructure as Code (IaC)?
Infrastructure as Code (IaC) is the practice of managing and provisioning infrastructure using code and templates instead of manual processes.
Popular IaC tools:

Terraform
Pulumi
OpenTofu
AWS CloudFormation
Azure ARM Templates
GCP Deployment Manager (CDM)


2️⃣ Terraform & Pulumi

Terraform: Declarative IaC tool by HashiCorp
Pulumi: IaC using general‑purpose languages (Python, Go, TypeScript)

Terraform is cloud‑agnostic and works across AWS, Azure, GCP, etc.

3️⃣ Why use IaC? (Benefits)

✅ Cost reduction
✅ Faster infrastructure deployment
✅ Reduced human errors
✅ Improved infrastructure consistency (Idempotent)
✅ Eliminates configuration drift
✅ Easy collaboration and reuse across teams

Key Interview Keyword:
👉 Idempotency – running the same code multiple times gives the same result.

4️⃣ What is Terraform State File?
Terraform uses a state file to track real infrastructure.
State file stores:

Current infrastructure status
Timestamp
Who made the changes
Which files were modified

💡 Interview Tip:
State enables Terraform to decide what to create, modify, or delete.

5️⃣ Declarative vs Imperative Approach
Declarative Method (Terraform)
You define WHAT you want, not HOW to do it.
Example:

10 servers
32 GB RAM
16 vCPUs
100 GB storage

Terraform figures out the steps automatically.
✅ Simple
✅ Less error‑prone
✅ Preferred for IaC

Imperative Method
You define step‑by‑step instructions to achieve the result.
Examples:

Bash / PowerShell scripts
Python scripts
Ansible playbooks

❌ Complex
❌ Requires detailed scripting
❌ Needs highly skilled engineers
👉 Terraform follows the Declarative approach.

6️⃣ Provisioning vs Configuration Management
Provisioning
Setting up infrastructure resources:

VM
Storage
Network
Load Balancer
Databases

Example tools: Terraform, CloudFormation

Configuration Management
Performed after provisioning:

Install software
Configure servers
Maintain systems

Tools:

Ansible
Chef
Puppet
SaltStack

👉 Terraform is mainly a provisioning tool, not configuration management.

7️⃣ Mutable vs Immutable Infrastructure
Mutable Infrastructure

Existing servers are updated
Software patches applied on same server
Changes accumulate over time

❌ Hard to rollback
❌ Configuration drift
❌ Security risks

Immutable Infrastructure

Servers never change after deployment
Any change creates a new version
Old version is replaced

✅ Easy rollback
✅ No configuration drift
✅ More secure
Interview Line:

“Immutable infra promotes consistency and reliability by replacing infrastructure instead of modifying it.”


8️⃣ Tools Used in Immutable Infrastructure

Virtualized platform → Packer (golden images)
Containerized platform → Docker (container images)


